00:16:38.800 --> 00:16:43.500
So one thing we've heard loud and clear
from developers is that this is not the

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:45.930
experience they want for their games.

00:16:46.100 --> 00:16:54.540
So we've added turn-based
timeouts in iOS 6 so that now,

00:16:54.650 --> 00:16:57.510
after a period of time that you specify,
Bill's turn will time out

00:16:57.510 --> 00:16:57.510
and it will pass to Claire.

00:16:57.760 --> 00:17:00.180
Claire can take her turn,
and now your game has

00:17:00.180 --> 00:17:01.740
a number of options.

00:17:01.840 --> 00:17:06.180
You can choose to simply drop Bill from
the game and continue on with,

00:17:06.250 --> 00:17:07.800
like, three players.

00:17:07.860 --> 00:17:11.640
Or you can give someone,
perhaps Claire or Aideen,

00:17:11.730 --> 00:17:14.740
the opportunity to invite
someone to replace Bill.

00:17:14.820 --> 00:17:18.920
Maybe you want to invite Edward and
keep on going with a four-player game.

00:17:19.080 --> 00:17:23.290
Or as we're going to do,
we're going to rearrange the participants

00:17:24.300 --> 00:17:27.010
so that Bill gets another chance.

00:17:27.350 --> 00:17:33.040
and Claire then passes the turn to Bill,
and it turns out he's at a restaurant,

00:17:33.040 --> 00:17:36.900
they have free Wi-Fi, lo and behold,
he gets the turn notification,

00:17:36.900 --> 00:17:39.210
and so instead of spending
time with his family,

00:17:39.210 --> 00:17:41.570
he starts playing the game.

00:17:41.880 --> 00:17:45.800
When he's done,
the notification passes to Deirdre,

00:17:45.940 --> 00:17:48.890
she gets the invitation,
she downloads the game,

00:17:48.910 --> 00:17:51.020
and she starts playing.

00:17:51.100 --> 00:17:55.530
So turn-based timeouts are
really a big deal to ensure

00:17:55.530 --> 00:17:57.460
that everyone gets to play.

00:17:57.540 --> 00:18:00.690
And by ensuring everyone gets to play,
you ensure everybody gets

00:18:00.690 --> 00:18:02.020
to download the game.

00:18:02.320 --> 00:18:05.320
The way you take advantage
of this couldn't be simpler.

00:18:05.320 --> 00:18:10.400
There's a new ntern with
next participants API.

00:18:10.400 --> 00:18:14.200
You call that and you pass
in an array of participants.

00:18:14.200 --> 00:18:16.980
That array is all the
participants in order that they

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:18.740
should take their next turn.

00:18:18.740 --> 00:18:23.370
And we recommend that the player who
just finished his turn be added to

00:18:23.400 --> 00:18:25.540
the array perhaps as the last player.

00:18:25.640 --> 00:18:29.700
And the reason for that is that's
the only way you can ensure

00:18:29.700 --> 00:18:34.300
that if everyone times out,
the turn passes back to someone

00:18:34.300 --> 00:18:36.560
who at least was present.

00:18:36.760 --> 00:18:40.490
And at that point, then,
perhaps your game can kick it

00:18:40.490 --> 00:18:42.920
off again or do something else.

00:18:42.920 --> 00:18:44.840
You can specify a timeout period.

00:18:44.840 --> 00:18:45.970
We have a number of constants.

00:18:46.080 --> 00:18:49.820
I believe we have, like, one day,
one week, one month, one millennia,

00:18:49.820 --> 00:18:50.940
that kind of thing.

00:18:51.070 --> 00:18:53.940
And also, naturally, the match data.

00:18:54.110 --> 00:18:57.620
Also in iOS 6,
we've added the ability to save

00:18:57.620 --> 00:19:00.000
match data during the turn.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:04.300
And this is really critical if you
have a game that has multiple phases.

00:19:04.300 --> 00:19:08.500
Or perhaps let's say you have like a
trivia game where with each question,

00:19:08.500 --> 00:19:10.940
