So you can build out all of
this functionality yourself,

00:29:08.820 --> 00:29:12.970
or you can take advantage
of what we've already built.

00:29:14.900 --> 00:29:17.970
Leaderboards, if you want to show a
specific leaderboard,

00:29:17.970 --> 00:29:19.120
it's really easy.

00:29:19.120 --> 00:29:27.080
Three lines more code, you tell us, hey,
let's show some leaderboards,

00:29:27.080 --> 00:29:27.080
the scope of the leaderboards,
and then which leaderboard to show.

00:29:27.930 --> 00:29:34.710
Similarly, achievements and challenges
are a single line extra code.

00:29:34.990 --> 00:29:38.550
So I think you'll find that taking
advantage of the new unified experience

00:29:38.950 --> 00:29:42.190
is a really easy addition for your game.

00:29:43.030 --> 00:29:46.950
Now, naturally, we didn't want to just
stop with leaderboards,

00:29:46.970 --> 00:29:49.360
achievements, and scores, right?

00:29:49.360 --> 00:29:52.380
Because there's so much
more to Game Center.

00:29:52.380 --> 00:29:55.620
There's all of that
multiplayer experience.

00:29:55.620 --> 00:30:01.900
And so in iOS 6,
we've completely revamped the

00:30:01.900 --> 00:30:01.900
multiplayer matchmaking experience.

00:30:02.060 --> 00:30:04.430
First of all, we streamlined it.

00:30:04.490 --> 00:30:08.900
So now you start off with the maximum
number of players that you specify.

00:30:08.950 --> 00:30:13.240
And this really helps your players
get in and get playing right away.

00:30:13.290 --> 00:30:18.570
Because if all they want
to do is play the game,

00:30:18.570 --> 00:30:18.570
they just tap play and they're playing.

00:30:18.720 --> 00:30:24.130
And they can remove players fairly
easy just by tapping on the X.

00:30:24.270 --> 00:30:29.090
They can add new players back in
by tapping on the resulting square.

00:30:29.240 --> 00:30:32.620
Then they can invite their friends
simply by tapping invite friends,

00:30:32.620 --> 00:30:36.860
and we have a new friend picker that
gives them the option to just tap,

00:30:36.960 --> 00:30:39.520
you know, three times,
they get exactly who

00:30:39.520 --> 00:30:42.280
they want in the game,
and tap next to send a

00:30:42.390 --> 00:30:44.140
personalized message.

00:30:44.140 --> 00:30:48.380
Or they can pick players that
they've played with recently.

00:30:48.380 --> 00:30:51.020
Now these don't have to be friends.

00:30:51.020 --> 00:30:54.600
They're just people that they
played this game with recently.

00:30:54.600 --> 00:30:57.680
So if they auto matched last
time and they just want to

00:30:57.680 --> 00:31:00.910
play with those folks again,
they don't have to, you know,

00:31:00.970 --> 00:31:03.310
send friend requests and
do all that rigmarole.

00:31:03.420 --> 00:31:06.610
They just jump back in,
pick the same people,

00:31:06.610 --> 00:31:08.130
and play a new game.

00:31:08.330 --> 00:31:12.950
And finally, what we think is going to be
a huge deal for everybody's

00:31:13.460 --> 00:31:16.170
game is local multiplayer.

00:31:16.490 --> 00:31:20.340
Now, you've always been able
to invite local players,

00:31:20.540 --> 00:31:22.220
but you had to do all the work.

00:31:22.220 --> 00:31:25.810
Buried deep down in the APIs was
the GK session stuff and you

00:31:25.860 --> 00:31:28.080
could find out who was out there.

00:31:28.080 --> 00:31:30.440
But it was a bit of work.

00:31:30.440 --> 00:31:33.870
Now we've built that right into
the multiplayer matchmaking APIs so

00:31:33.870 --> 00:31:36.640
that you don't have to do anything.

00:31:36.720 --> 00:31:38.940
The theory being, hey,
Bill is on his way to

00:31:38.940 --> 00:31:42.790
Yosemite in the backseat,
his two kids would love to play a game,

00:31:42.810 --> 00:31:43.460
right?

00:31:43.460 --> 00:31:47.230
Before, the game had to be coded
to especially handle that.

00:31:47.260 --> 00:31:49.850
Now every game can handle that.

00:31:49.860 --> 00:31:53.730
I think this is a big deal,
especially when it comes

00:31:53.730 --> 00:31:55.880
to party circumstances.

00:31:57.530 --> 00:32:01.110
Now, bringing up the multiplayer
matchmaking experience is a

00:32:01.300 --> 00:32:04.320
little bit more complicated,
but then again, you'd expect it to be,

00:32:04.370 --> 00:32:04.790
right?

00:32:04.980 --> 00:32:07.400
First,
you have to tell us about your match.

00:32:07.510 --> 00:32:09.240
What's the minimum number of players?

00:32:09.380 --> 00:32:11.400
What's the maximum number of players?

00:32:11.430 --> 00:32:12.960
And there's some other options.

00:32:13.020 --> 00:32:18.390
If you're interested,
you really should go to the

00:32:18.390 --> 00:32:18.390
multiplayer gaming session on Thursday.

00:32:19.310 --> 00:32:24.040
After that,
you create the view controller.

00:32:24.040 --> 00:32:28.080
You set your delegates so that you can
know about some of the matchmaking events

00:32:28.310 --> 00:32:30.860
that will occur before the game starts.

00:32:30.860 --> 00:32:34.220
And then, obviously,
you want to present that so that

00:32:34.220 --> 00:32:36.570
your players can interact with it.

00:32:36.950 --> 00:32:38.280
And that's it.

00:32:38.390 --> 00:32:41.630
When you're done there,
your delegate will get a callback saying,

00:32:41.690 --> 00:32:44.300
"Game's ready," and off you go.

00:32:44.430 --> 00:32:46.190
You get dropped right into the game.

00:32:46.400 --> 00:32:52.190
You can use the same multiplayer
APIs you're familiar with,

00:32:52.190 --> 00:32:54.650
and your game goes.

00:32:55.940 --> 00:33:00.240
That's the baseline level of polish
that we think every game is going to

00:33:00.240 --> 00:33:03.060
require in order to be successful.

00:33:03.060 --> 00:33:06.180
You'll need to be able
to send challenges,

00:33:06.180 --> 00:33:10.860
share scores, and multiplayer matching
with local players.

00:33:10.950 --> 00:33:12.790
It's going to be great.

00:33:14.230 --> 00:33:18.150
All of these things combined
together allow you to focus

00:33:18.150 --> 00:33:20.460
on what's really important.

00:33:20.460 --> 00:33:23.100
And what's really important
is building a fun game.

00:33:23.100 --> 00:33:24.100
Right?

00:33:24.100 --> 00:33:27.210
I mean,
that's why people play your games.

00:33:27.690 --> 00:33:32.190
Now, there's a lot of things that we've
seen that go into making a fun game,

00:33:32.400 --> 00:33:35.290
but one of the ones that we'd
like to highlight today is the

00:33:35.780 --> 00:33:41.120
games that focus on players,
scores, and achievements.

00:33:41.120 --> 00:33:44.450
From the very beginning,
they're the ones that wind

00:33:44.450 --> 00:33:46.040
up being the most fun.

00:33:46.040 --> 00:33:50.590
If you think about games like
Jetpack Joyride and Temple Run,

00:33:50.590 --> 00:33:55.100
as you're running through the game,
as you're flying through the lab,

00:33:55.100 --> 00:33:56.560
what do you see?

00:33:56.560 --> 00:33:59.930
You see these little banners with
your buddies' names on them because

00:34:00.040 --> 00:34:01.640
you've just passed their distance.

00:34:01.640 --> 00:34:05.330
And that gives you the
immersive experience that

00:34:05.330 --> 00:34:07.870
really draws you into the game.

00:34:09.380 --> 00:34:14.060
And we'd like to challenge you to
go a little bit further than that.

00:34:14.060 --> 00:34:18.610
We'd like to take advantage of
something you heard about this morning,

00:34:18.610 --> 00:34:21.660
the context on a GK score.

00:34:21.660 --> 00:34:25.740
This really is an
underused bit of goodness.

00:34:25.740 --> 00:34:30.040
You have 64 bits that
you can do anything with.

00:34:30.040 --> 00:34:33.750
Any crazy idea that pops into your head,
this is your data.

00:34:33.830 --> 00:34:37.190
So let's look at a couple of things
that we were able to think of,

00:34:37.190 --> 00:34:41.420
and I'm sure you'll come up
with something even better.

00:34:41.420 --> 00:34:44.380
So first of all, we've got space pylon,
right?

00:34:44.380 --> 00:34:47.990
Wouldn't it be nice if we
took two bits and encoded the

00:34:47.990 --> 00:34:50.510
color scheme of the spaceship?

00:34:53.780 --> 00:34:58.600
Well, we still have 62 bits to work with,
so let's take another four to six bits

00:34:58.730 --> 00:35:01.890
and encode the style of spaceship.

00:35:02.180 --> 00:35:04.440
So now I know whether I'm
flying the Alliance fighter

00:35:04.440 --> 00:35:07.540
jet or the Armada Raider.

00:35:07.540 --> 00:35:09.710
All there in the scores.

00:35:09.780 --> 00:35:13.870
And that gives me a lot of power
as I'm showing my leaderboards.

00:35:13.880 --> 00:35:18.850
So, maybe at the end of the game I can
show up all the players who are

00:35:18.860 --> 00:35:20.200
doing a little bit better than me.

00:35:20.200 --> 00:35:21.400
All my friends, right?

00:35:21.400 --> 00:35:24.900
I mean, this is a pretty common
experience in games.

00:35:24.900 --> 00:35:27.320
Here's your score,
here's the guys who are ahead of you.

00:35:27.570 --> 00:35:29.890
Well,
wouldn't it be great if your players

00:35:29.890 --> 00:35:35.220
could tap on those scores and they
could see exactly the ship configuration

00:35:35.320 --> 00:35:41.880
or the player class or the weapons or
whatever that makes sense to that score?

00:35:41.880 --> 00:35:46.270
Wouldn't it be neat if they could say,
"Oh, I could get that and I bet that

00:35:46.270 --> 00:35:48.730
would help me play the game."

00:35:49.180 --> 00:35:54.980
Now, 64 bits is a lot,
but it's not everything, right?

00:35:55.590 --> 00:36:01.080
You can't encode all of the data that
they did this morning in 64 bits.

00:36:01.080 --> 00:36:03.060
It's just not possible.

00:36:03.060 --> 00:36:07.480
So what you can do is you can
collect all of the telemetry,

00:36:07.480 --> 00:36:15.360
all of the random number seeds,
all of the data that you needed to do to

00:36:15.360 --> 00:36:18.210
create that experience and save it off
to a server somewhere as a ghost lap.

00:36:18.950 --> 00:36:22.700
And then you can replay that
information at any time.

00:36:22.700 --> 00:36:28.360
So instead of just seeing, oh, look,
he was flying a red Alliance fighter jet,

00:36:28.480 --> 00:36:32.710
I can actually see the path that
he took around the course that

00:36:32.710 --> 00:36:35.220
helped him get such a high score.

00:36:38.630 --> 00:36:42.020
Now, scores and context,
that's pretty cool, right?

00:36:42.050 --> 00:36:46.100
And there's great things that you
can do by putting just a little bit

00:36:46.100 --> 00:36:50.820
more information into the scores so
that you can pull it back out later.

00:36:50.820 --> 00:36:58.820
But where it gets really cool
is when you add challenges,

00:36:58.820 --> 00:37:01.250
as you saw this morning.

00:37:01.250 --> 00:37:01.250
Because scores and context and challenges

00:37:01.520 --> 00:37:03.320
That's pure awesome.

00:37:03.320 --> 00:37:08.610
The sorts of things that we saw this
morning with the ghost lap as Adam and

00:37:08.610 --> 00:37:12.540
Joe were competing right there,
that's fantastic.

00:37:12.690 --> 00:37:16.640
We'd love to see you guys take
advantage of things like that.

00:37:16.700 --> 00:37:22.890
And I know it's a little
bit extra work on your part,

00:37:22.960 --> 00:37:25.070
but it really is going to give a
great experience for your players.

00:37:25.920 --> 00:37:29.550
So instead of getting my
challenge to finish the course in

00:37:29.610 --> 00:37:34.220
under 3 minutes and 15 seconds,
in any old fighter that I want to fly,

00:37:34.280 --> 00:37:37.590
wouldn't it be great if your
players could have the option of

00:37:37.590 --> 00:37:41.740
flying in exactly the configuration
that the challenger flew in?

00:37:42.230 --> 00:37:46.050
It would really enrich
the experience for them.

00:37:47.640 --> 00:37:50.640
Now,
game groups are another key technology

00:37:51.010 --> 00:37:53.320
that you can take advantage of.

00:37:53.480 --> 00:37:56.860
to make your games just
that more immersive?

00:37:56.930 --> 00:38:01.790
So for example, Aideen flies Alliance and
Bill flies Armada.

00:38:01.940 --> 00:38:03.350
Great games.

00:38:03.440 --> 00:38:07.120
They play together,
they can fly on common racecourses,

00:38:07.120 --> 00:38:07.760
right?

00:38:07.920 --> 00:38:12.250
But wouldn't it be great to give
Aideen the experience of playing

00:38:12.250 --> 00:38:14.970
Armada in a multiplayer setting?

00:38:15.160 --> 00:38:19.900
And the way you can do that,
and encourage Aideen to try out

00:38:20.020 --> 00:38:25.250
the Armada version of the game,
is take advantage of player attributes

00:38:25.870 --> 00:38:30.340
when you set up the matchmaking,
so that Bill is the host,

00:38:30.420 --> 00:38:37.020
and when the game gets connected,
Aideen is sent all of the assets,

00:38:37.120 --> 00:38:41.300
so that she has the opportunity
to fly one of the Armada Raiders,

00:38:41.380 --> 00:38:45.100
and fly on one of the
cool Armada racecourses,

00:38:45.180 --> 00:38:48.430
with all the alien buildings
and the whole nine yards.

00:38:48.820 --> 00:38:54.940
This is a great way to expose players to
games that they might not otherwise have.

00:38:54.940 --> 00:38:58.010
All part of the game
group that you've built.

00:38:58.270 --> 00:39:03.980
And we think it's going to be a great
way to expose people to your games.

00:39:03.980 --> 00:39:07.010
So those are just a couple of
Game Center ways that you can

00:39:07.010 --> 00:39:10.220
enhance your games and make
them a little bit more fun.

00:39:10.300 --> 00:39:17.890
There's a couple of other technologies
that you might have heard about

00:39:17.900 --> 00:39:21.390
this morning that we also think
are a great way to raise the bar

00:39:21.390 --> 00:39:21.390
on the fun level of your game.

00:39:22.070 --> 00:39:23.640
The first is Airplay.

00:39:23.640 --> 00:39:28.080
Airplay is a perfect match
for turn-based games.

00:39:28.080 --> 00:39:32.050
If you think about it,
when you're playing a board game,

00:39:32.150 --> 00:39:36.070
you've got this big public experience,
the board.

00:39:36.080 --> 00:39:40.460
Maybe you're playing Railroad Empire,
and you can see the routes that

00:39:40.460 --> 00:39:42.660
your buddies have all claimed.

00:39:42.660 --> 00:39:45.630
You can see whatever special
actions are in effect.

00:39:45.630 --> 00:39:50.260
There's all this public information,
but then there's the private information,

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:50.720
right?

00:39:50.720 --> 00:39:52.720
That's the information on your device.

00:39:52.720 --> 00:39:56.850
And maybe that's your special actions
or your special abilities or the

00:39:56.850 --> 00:39:58.570
routes you're trying to complete.

00:39:58.580 --> 00:40:00.950
And it's a perfect match here.

00:40:00.950 --> 00:40:05.660
Only one device has to be
broadcasting to the big screen,

00:40:05.660 --> 00:40:09.660
and you don't have to worry about
frame rates or anything else like that,

00:40:09.910 --> 00:40:13.660
because by and large,
it's a pretty static display.

00:40:14.170 --> 00:40:15.020
Fantastic fit.

00:40:15.060 --> 00:40:17.360
Now, also,

00:40:18.900 --> 00:40:22.340
Party games like this are a
great fit for local multiplayer,

00:40:22.350 --> 00:40:26.050
right, because all it takes is one person
to start up the game and everybody

00:40:26.050 --> 00:40:27.440
else can just jump right in.

00:40:27.500 --> 00:40:29.030
Don't even have to know they're there.

00:40:29.250 --> 00:40:31.050
They can just jump in, play the game.

00:40:31.330 --> 00:40:34.320
Fantastic for party games.

00:40:34.460 --> 00:40:38.480
The other big one, frankly, is iCloud.

00:40:39.230 --> 00:40:42.040
How many times have you
been playing a game,

00:40:42.040 --> 00:40:45.470
you've gotten lots of power-ups,
you've bought special

00:40:45.500 --> 00:40:49.630
equipment for your ship,
then you move over to your iPad,

00:40:49.760 --> 00:40:51.290
and it's gone?

00:40:52.630 --> 00:40:56.240
It's not just long-running
games that have game state.

00:40:56.340 --> 00:41:00.580
Sure, in your dungeon crawl,
you want to save exactly where you

00:41:00.580 --> 00:41:04.980
are in the dungeon and what monsters
you killed and what loot is where.

00:41:04.980 --> 00:41:09.050
But it also is really important
for short-running games.

00:41:09.140 --> 00:41:13.670
So it's a great idea at any point
that your game is complete to save

00:41:13.670 --> 00:41:19.000
that information up to iCloud so
that it's available across devices.

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:22.500
So when I go home and I play on my iPad,

00:41:23.410 --> 00:41:26.620
I get all of the same achievements
and power-ups and coins and everything

00:41:26.620 --> 00:41:31.640
else that I've been playing with all
day long instead of doing my work.

00:41:31.640 --> 00:41:37.910
And the key to all of this is you
want to use the ID of the game

00:41:37.910 --> 00:41:41.290
group as the index on iCloud.

00:41:41.380 --> 00:41:47.970
Because that will give you a common
index across all of your games so that

00:41:47.970 --> 00:41:47.970
they can all access the same data.

00:41:51.060 --> 00:41:53.580
So those are a couple of things
that we want you to think about

00:41:53.640 --> 00:41:58.080
